  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "[Figure 1 here] Paradigm -Language Model￼s: Deep Learning in NLPIn general terms, a language model is a method that predicts the next word in a sequence, given the previous words.",
    "There are two main types of language models: n-gram models and artificial neural network based models.",
    "N-gram models predict words from a fixed window of previous words, with probabilities estimated by counting the frequencies of these n-grams in a corpus [27].",
    "N-gram language models can be simple and efficient, but suffer from poor generalisation to words and word sequences not seen in the training data -by predicting next words using only the words that immediately precede, n-gram models ignore useful information from more distant words in a text [29].",
    "Neural language models are more complex and computationally expensive, but offer many unique advantages due to their ability to learn vector representations from the text itself."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
